WEBVTT

00:01.330 --> 00:07.899
We're in the office of Bruce McClendon in the 
municipal building of Fort Worth. Bruce, after

00:09.140 --> 00:20.615
you left Galveston, you went to Beaumont, and tell 
us a little bit about the program in Beaumont and

00:09.140 --> 00:20.615
what your role in that was. Well, Beaumont was just 
as much of a challenge as Galveston in that It was

00:27.757 --> 00:29.400
the right time. Something needed to be done and 
people wanted it done. The manager who hired me,

00:33.186 --> 00:37.953
Ray Riley, was outstanding. He and his classmates 
from that particular class of KU all turned out to

00:38.173 --> 00:45.104
be very successful. It's Anderson in Dallas, Lou 
Fox in San Antonio, Muhlenbeck, who was down in

00:47.990 --> 00:51.899
Galveston, and Ray Riley. And I thought Ray Riley 
was the one who was more skilled, more gifted as a

00:52.540 --> 00:58.254
manager than any of the others. He is now working in 
the private sector and the head of a major

00:58.274 --> 01:04.969
corporation down here in the Beaumont area, a very 
successful individual. But Ray had a little bit of

01:05.523 --> 01:08.792
a planning background. He had interned up in the 
Kansas City, Lawrence area in a planning kind of

01:08.872 --> 01:15.670
capacity. So he knew the terminology, he knew the 
techniques, he knew the deficiencies that

01:16.252 --> 01:22.047
existed, and he gave me broad marching orders to 
basically create a planning program to do

01:22.027 --> 01:28.775
something with respect to planning. Everything 
they had was 20 or 30 years old. They had old

01:32.220 --> 01:38.808
comprehensive plans, old zoning, old 
subdivision regulations, no capital

01:32.220 --> 01:38.808
improvements programming. A planner's dream. I 
mean, here you're given the resources and the

01:39.829 --> 01:42.913
direction to do something. Who had been the 
planning director previously? Somebody from

01:46.217 --> 01:48.760
Chicago had been brought in for a couple of years. 
Anderson, I believe, was his name, John Anderson.

01:53.685 --> 01:57.969
And John was a regional, had come from a regional 
planning commission. And there was a big jump from

01:58.749 --> 02:01.992
regional planning to municipal planning. I don't 
think John and I have been able to make that jump.

02:04.535 --> 02:07.317
And he had a young staff out of the way, part of the 
state. So he really didn't have

02:07.398 --> 02:17.447
the staff in place or the experience, in my 
judgment, to be as effective as he put it in. And he

02:18.187 --> 02:20.788
tended to sit on his staff a little bit. I was a 
little bit afraid of them for the younger ones that

02:21.140 --> 02:27.647
did have some energy initiative. Well, our first 
priority was to do the zoning ordinance. And it

02:30.489 --> 02:34.714
took about a year, year and a half, very 
controversial. They had a 25-year-old zoning

02:34.794 --> 02:39.979
ordinance, Beaumont, that historically did 
anti-regulation. They had passed zoning in

02:39.999 --> 02:42.201
something like 1948. And then the year after that, 
the public referendum, they rejected zoning. And

02:47.546 --> 02:51.130
then back in about 1954, 55, the zoning wave came 
again and basically the development community

02:51.110 --> 03:02.212
produced an ordinance that, you know, was kind of 
one of those things where if we're going to have

02:51.110 --> 03:02.212
zoning, it might be something we can live with. So 
we had this ordinance. It was only about 40 pages

03:03.875 --> 03:06.660
long. Very skimpy, cumulative zoning. It was more 
of a devious kind of ordinance. The district

03:14.436 --> 03:25.447
labels, for example, didn't link up to what the 
district really was, so you could come in and get R3

03:14.436 --> 03:25.447
zoning, residential multifamily zoning, and 
they ended up allowing commercial, too. It was all

03:25.467 --> 03:35.877
sorts of... Well, then you revised the zoning 
ordinance, and then after that, what was the...

03:25.467 --> 03:35.877
Revised the zoning ordinance, very 
controversial, very emotional experience. It

03:36.278 --> 03:38.700
took us a year and a half because the ordinance was 
so old. Recall was threatened. Lots of things

03:40.980 --> 03:42.162
happened there. But when the smoke finally 
cleared on that, we got a new ordinance in place

03:42.202 --> 03:51.197
that's a very good format, good model for the 
format that can be used by other places. To

03:51.738 --> 04:00.772
implement, as part of the implementation 
process, we incorporated some aspects of our plan

03:51.738 --> 04:00.772
into our zoning ordinance, which makes that a 
little bit unique in that sense. And we used that as

04:00.792 --> 04:05.380
a springboard then to develop our comprehensive 
plan. They had been trying to do a comprehensive

04:05.360 --> 04:10.207
plan for about five years, but there was a lot of 
data in place. It meant in a very short period of

04:10.827 --> 04:17.476
time, less than a year, we were able to reduce the 
land use. Really, the first element was the park

04:17.677 --> 04:24.746
and open space element, followed shortly 
thereafter by the land use element of the

04:17.677 --> 04:24.746
comprehensive plan. We did the park and open space 
because, A, we needed something less

04:24.766 --> 04:30.374
controversial at the zoning ordinance. We had to 
try to earn our spurs and win our way back into the

04:30.394 --> 04:34.860
community. So we did the park and open space plan, 
did establish the process and the format,

04:35.144 --> 04:47.160
issue-oriented planning process with 
measurable objectives as a result of the final

04:35.144 --> 04:47.160
product. We had a plan that we called, that we 
described as the goals, objectives, policies,

04:47.220 --> 04:53.227
and proposals. We presented this in the graphic 
format. We tried to use the unified submarine

04:55.190 --> 04:58.234
approach of Kent. We produced, our plan that was 
actually published was a fold-out brochure that

05:03.308 --> 05:07.576
fit into the pocket of the plan itself. The next 
step was to do the land use plan. The land use plan

05:12.065 --> 05:13.788
was completed while I was there. We were able to go 
through one and I think two update cycles of the

05:13.808 --> 05:21.503
park and open space plan where we, in essence, 
evaluated our accomplishments during the past

05:21.483 --> 05:31.982
year, identified new issues that emerged, 
proposed solutions or treatments to those

05:21.483 --> 05:31.982
issues, and set a work program for the following 
year. We called it an action plan, which was really

05:32.082 --> 05:39.155
a one-year detailed program for implementation 
of our plan. We were able to start the cycle on the

05:39.415 --> 05:42.040
land use element. When the plans were adopted, 
they contained language that required that they

05:42.205 --> 05:50.073
be reviewed and updated annually, and report from 
the staff and commission actioned by the city

05:42.205 --> 05:50.073
council. Did it bother you at all that the zoning 
ordinance rewrite preceded the development of

05:50.454 --> 05:59.083
the comprehensive plan? Sure. In theory, you 
know, we all, everybody knows the theory that we

05:59.403 --> 06:03.247
should be planning before we do zoning. And the one 
reason it took us a year and a half to do the zoning

06:03.687 --> 06:09.934
was because we did some of the planning. With your 
left hand while you were doing the zoning with your

06:09.914 --> 06:12.717
right, I suppose. Well, and we integrated into the 
ordinance. I mean, because people couldn't

06:14.659 --> 06:16.060
understand. If we had been trying to do the 
planning on the side, we wouldn't have gone very

06:16.100 --> 06:19.544
far. So we took elements of the plan, the 
principles, concepts, and standards for

06:19.584 --> 06:25.750
residential, commercial, and industrial 
development. These were actually integrated

06:26.050 --> 06:29.774
into the text of the plan itself. So there was an 
understanding of the planning foundation of the

06:30.255 --> 06:34.259
ordinance that we were going through. This was the 
only thing I could do because The priority was to do

06:36.661 --> 06:39.747
the update to zoning ordinance. The council 
wanted it, the manager wanted it, so we had to

06:39.767 --> 06:43.374
pursue it. What's really ironic about that is when 
the development community tried to stop the

06:43.975 --> 06:58.483
updating process, and that's one reason why I drug 
out for a year and a half, but as their last gas

06:43.975 --> 06:58.483
effort to stop it, they started lecturing the 
council that it was important that you do planning

06:59.240 --> 07:09.933
before you do zoning, and that we ought to defer the 
plan, the zoning, until we can complete updating

06:59.240 --> 07:09.933
the comprehensive plan. That's ironic. Yeah, it 
was really, really interesting. And, of course,

07:14.619 --> 07:21.168
once we finished the plan, the ordinance, the 
development community said, well, what's all the

07:14.619 --> 07:21.168
rush on the plan now? Uh-huh. Sure. But it was 
actually the Chamber of Commerce that was beating

07:24.383 --> 07:29.831
the drums at the very end for a comprehensive plan. 
It's the way it ought to be. Yes, it should have

07:32.475 --> 07:33.336
been. Where were they when I got there? So I was 
there three and a half, four years and the last

07:36.841 --> 07:41.768
thing that we did was the capital improvements 
program. The first time that city had a legitimate

07:44.285 --> 07:57.800
real world program, capital improvements 
program with priorities, analysis of the fiscal

07:44.285 --> 07:57.800
funding sources, identification of where the 
money was going to come from to fund the various

07:44.285 --> 07:57.800
capital projects. And the plan itself was 
reviewed annually, I suppose, as a basis for the

07:58.441 --> 08:02.125
CIP. The plan, in fact, that was the first block we 
checked was conformance with the plan and whether

08:02.145 --> 08:11.535
or not we were integrating or implementing the 
comprehensive plan. Are there any cities that

08:11.718 --> 08:20.953
you're aware of in Texas that have this kind of 
relationship between zoning and CIP and the

08:11.718 --> 08:20.953
conference plans? No, to my knowledge, the 
Beaumont system is just far superior. We took the

08:26.441 --> 08:28.825
theory and we made it work there. Terrific 
opportunity. You know, again, the manager was

08:30.367 --> 08:31.749
there. We had, Maury Myers was the mayor who was 
He's probably the most outstanding mayor in the

08:35.275 --> 08:38.202
United States. He and Henry Cisneros are peas in a 
pod in terms of their judgmental leadership

08:38.242 --> 08:43.595
ability. He resigned, or when his term was up, he 
did not run again. And he is now the mayor again

08:47.664 --> 08:51.393
because of all the trouble they're having. In 
Beaumont, he came back. and put himself back in the

08:53.618 --> 08:56.661
harness and ran for office again. Because of the 
economy? Because of the economy and the downturn.

08:59.405 --> 09:02.889
