09:04.470 --> 09:07.614
again, it wasn't because the community didn't 
want him. It was that he wanted to do other things,

09:07.754 --> 09:10.698
and he had given his public service. Just looking 
back over your career here in Texas, beginning

09:12.079 --> 09:18.867
with Corpus Christi and then moving on to 
Galveston and then Beaumont and Fort Worth, It

09:19.420 --> 09:44.989
sounds to me like you tried certain things out 
initially in Corpus Christi and were frustrated

09:19.420 --> 09:44.989
there because of management and the whole 
political climate, then moved on to Gauss and you

09:19.420 --> 09:44.989
were able to do a little bit more, and then when you 
got to Beaumont you found that the ground had

09:19.420 --> 09:44.989
already been fertilized, so that you were given 
more or less a free hand to exercise theory and

09:45.290 --> 09:47.736
apply it to a practical situation. That's a very 
good summary. There is no question that in terms of

09:49.480 --> 09:54.451
effectiveness, my most effective program was 
BOVA. On a scale of 1 to 10, it was a 9. In Galveston,

10:00.848 --> 10:07.016
Because I was there shorter and there was so much 
less that I could do, I would say my effectiveness

10:00.848 --> 10:07.016
was a seven. But I was real pleased with the 
Galveston achievements, too. We were able to, the

10:09.980 --> 10:12.162
bottom line was results. We produced big results. 
There was tremendous payback in Galveston. But in

10:15.987 --> 10:20.934
Beaumont, I was able to put the theory to practice 
and something to come from it. And the

10:21.414 --> 10:24.558
implementation resulted and took place. So it was 
a planner's dream. Now, you were in Beaumont at the

10:28.220 --> 10:33.327
time that you were elected to the presidency of 
APA. That's right. What were the circumstances

10:34.589 --> 10:40.057
that prompted you to run for national office? 
Well, I had been president of the Texas chapter of

10:40.077 --> 10:46.326
APA. Who was the vice president then? Who was the 
vice president then? I couldn't tell you. I don't

10:54.962 --> 10:55.663
know. You'll find out. It's funny. Sarah Jane was 
the secretary and treasurer on that board. I do not

11:02.476 --> 11:04.439
remember who the vice president was. We'll fill it 
in later. In my involvement is the chapter

11:07.285 --> 11:09.850
president. I serve in the chapter president's 
council, which is a board of chapter presidents

11:09.950 --> 11:22.013
all across the country that meets at the national 
level and advise and serves in a little bit of an

11:09.950 --> 11:22.013
advisory capacity to the national APA board. 
Well, in that capacity, we dealt with primarily

11:22.614 --> 11:29.226
the budget issue. increasing the dues and the 
National Board was of the opinion we needed to

11:29.206 --> 11:35.842
increase our dues a substantial amount, 20, 25 
percent. I was of the opinion and other members of

11:37.065 --> 11:46.067
the chapter that if there was a big gap between the 
National Board and what the members and what the

11:37.065 --> 11:46.067
members felt and wanted from their organization. 
And I met those people on the National Board and

11:48.147 --> 11:54.540
they were respected, influential, higher up 
people in planning. And my assessment of them was

11:55.201 --> 11:58.708
that they weren't close to the customer. That they 
had been involved in the profession for so many

11:58.728 --> 12:05.001
years and had risen to such a level that they 
couldn't remember their roots. their

12:05.487 --> 12:12.877
experiences as planter ones and planter twos, and 
they didn't have contact with these entry-level

12:05.487 --> 12:12.877
or mid-range type planters. So they didn't know 
what the heart of the profession was all about

12:13.298 --> 12:16.943
anymore. And I thought they were insensitive and 
uncaring in a sense, and very egotistical. It was

12:22.851 --> 12:25.395
almost the all AICP kind of thing. I really did 
perceive that they didn't really care. And we

12:27.838 --> 12:34.988
thought and we did a lot of work as the chapter 
presidents to advise the APA board. And the

12:38.370 --> 12:45.437
response from the APA board was just to brush us off 
as if we didn't know anything, didn't have

12:38.370 --> 12:45.437
anything to contribute. And their view was they 
knew as much about the organization and the needs

12:46.158 --> 12:55.567
of the members as we did, and that they were in touch 
with the membership and it was us, the chapter

12:46.158 --> 12:55.567
presidents, that were out of touch. And the 
national board, as I remember at that time, had

12:56.528 --> 13:05.076
historically been composed of people from The 
Eastern Seaboard community. From the Eastern

13:06.622 --> 13:16.010
Seaboard, and they were predominantly 
academicians with a sprinkling of practicing

13:06.622 --> 13:16.010
consultants. Probably on a 21-member board, I 
think only two or three may have been city planner

13:16.030 --> 13:26.720
types, you know, senior planners, or they were 
most of, you know, a planning director kind of

13:16.030 --> 13:26.720
person. Sure. They were not what the heart of the 
organization was. Because we can't put down

13:30.243 --> 13:31.864
academicians. No, only in the sense of the 
domination. I don't think. I saw something that

13:35.583 --> 13:42.292
says that the academic community constitutes 8% 
or 9% of the APA membership. If you're

13:42.753 --> 13:48.922
representing 8% of the membership and you have 60% 
of the board, there's an imbalance there. And

13:49.583 --> 13:51.806
there was an imbalance. So I came home and I was 
madder than hell from the meeting. And the more I

13:55.571 --> 13:59.717
started paying attention to what APA was doing, 
and the little newsletters that they would send

13:59.697 --> 14:03.004
out in their news and whatever it is. It became 
clearer and clearer to me that there wasn't

14:03.485 --> 14:13.605
grassroots inaction there, that the board had 
lost touch with the membership. other chapter

14:13.906 --> 14:16.589
presidents shared this frustration with me. And 
they called me and said, and I had been, as you know

14:17.150 --> 14:25.840
me, I had been pretty visible in my capacity on the 
chapter presidents council. I'm very

14:25.920 --> 14:29.685
opinionated and I'm a strong fighter and a 
promoter. And so I've promoted our position very

14:30.166 --> 14:34.531
strongly and impressed some people. They felt 
like here's a person who cares and here's a person

14:35.011 --> 14:38.415
who can carry our banner. So there were folks that 
called me and said, we need to do something about

14:40.518 --> 14:50.394
billing candidates, running for the board, 
trying to make our position known, and have a

14:40.518 --> 14:50.394
referendum on what it is we're all about. So I said, 
well, let me see if we can find somebody. So I tried

14:53.699 --> 15:01.833
to call, I tried to get Mary Lou Henry, who was the 
person I knew most about, who just, I'd followed

14:53.699 --> 15:01.833
her as chapter president or at this point here. 
Really, she'd been out of office for one term

15:02.414 --> 15:04.878
before I followed her. And Mary Lou, was a 
knowledgeable, informed, educated, just

15:08.075 --> 15:12.101
outstanding individual. So I tried to get Mary Lou 
to run for the board and for the president. I said,

15:15.927 --> 15:17.269
that's how you're going to make a statement. One 
position out of 21 can't do anything unless it's

15:17.930 --> 15:21.436
the president. So I tried to talk Mary Lou into 
running. She was appreciative of the offer, but

15:24.861 --> 15:31.872
couldn't do it because a good friend of hers from 
California Okay, at Pomona.

15:37.697 --> 15:39.340
Cal State at Pomona. Margarita McCoy. Margarita 
