25:20.295 --> 25:24.184
tend to come from the grassroots volunteer 
perspective, and I wanted to see the organization

25:24.788 --> 25:30.193
build on the strength of our volunteers, not be 
centralized. I was promoting decentralization,

25:30.353 --> 25:33.516
he was promoting centralization. Well, that was 
the basic difference between ASPO and APA, or AIP

25:34.017 --> 25:47.590
in those days, was that AIP had a chapter 
structure, and it could rely on its membership

25:34.017 --> 25:47.590
throughout the country. What I tried to do was take 
the strengths of both organizations and build on

25:51.434 --> 25:58.847
them and get rid of the weaknesses and weed those 
things out, the things that we weren't doing well

25:51.434 --> 25:58.847
or that were detrimental. There were many things 
ASPO did that are very solid, such as the technical

26:00.209 --> 26:04.797
publications. No question, they had a superior 
Their program was of more value to me growing up as a

26:07.162 --> 26:10.686
planner than AIP. AIP did a better job of sharing 
the grassroots, the networking kind of thing, to

26:11.327 --> 26:22.061
check the functions, getting out where I was as an 
entry-level person where I couldn't go to some of

26:11.327 --> 26:22.061
the national things. So what we really needed to do 
