then. We've talked about Beaumont, and we've 
talked about your role with National APA and, of

29:47.351 --> 29:55.003
course, the Texas Chapter APA. Now we are in Fort 
Worth. How about if I hit Arlington for about five

29:58.468 --> 30:01.853
minutes? Okay. All right. We don't want to forget 
Arlington. Yeah, Arlington, I'd like to forget

30:05.777 --> 30:08.061
Arlington. Everybody has an Arlington in their 
record somewhere, and I've got one, and that's

30:08.201 --> 30:14.812
Arlington. In contrast to Beaumont, which was the 
height of my career in terms of effectiveness,

30:14.832 --> 30:22.285
Arlington was the absolute low point in my career 
in effectiveness. I was not able to institute the

30:23.146 --> 30:29.537
programs and produce the products and results 
that I wanted to do. What were the reasons for that?

30:31.798 --> 30:42.812
Well, I came into a community that was very smug, a 
sense of arrogance, of superiority, that they

30:31.798 --> 30:42.812
were God's gift to the world. You know, Arlington 
had grown tremendously in population in the past

30:43.593 --> 30:53.265
10 or 20 years, from a population of 20,000 to 200 
and almost 50,000. Rapid growth. They made the

30:55.568 --> 30:59.693
classic management mistake of... assuming that 
luck was good management. They assumed, because

31:03.388 --> 31:08.376
everything was relatively okay, that what they'd 
been doing was profitable. In fact, it was the

31:08.857 --> 31:10.480
Houston Syndrome. They were in an ideal location 
between Dallas and Fort Worth. They were gaining

31:14.888 --> 31:19.015
all the benefits of everybody around them. 
through no fault of their own or no actions of their

31:19.670 --> 31:22.574
own, their location. It was a traditional real 
estate story about one of the three most important

31:22.614 --> 31:31.508
factors in real estate investment, location, 
location, location. Hey, Arlington had the

31:31.548 --> 31:32.970
location. They had a strong mayor who early in his 
career He used a Chamber of Commerce approach. He

31:38.727 --> 31:43.872
brought in General Motors and Washington 
Senators, became a Texas Rangers. What was his

31:44.433 --> 31:45.694
name? Vandergrift. Outstanding individual. He 
had the Chevrolet Buick. Chevrolet dealer, yeah.

31:50.880 --> 31:53.362
Well, wasn't he also big in Texas Municipal 
League? I doubt it. If he was, it would surprise me,

31:54.764 --> 31:56.826
but he might have been. He had more of a Chamber of 
Commerce approach, not really in the government.

32:01.271 --> 32:04.614
So I'd be surprised if he was involved in a 
government organization, but he could have been.

32:05.415 --> 32:06.096
But... had a planning commission that was 
dominated by a real estate interest. I said, well,

32:12.143 --> 32:16.008
good grief, who's on here that represents the 
citizens? And there was one woman on there,

32:16.028 --> 32:20.033
housewife, and she was working for the Chamber of 
Commerce. And I said, well, how about the guy from

32:20.333 --> 32:23.196
the university? I said, geez, at least there's an 
academic influence on here. And it turns out that

32:26.100 --> 32:35.391
he was from the School of Business at UTA, which has 
a completely different philosophy than a liberal

32:26.100 --> 32:35.391
arts kind of professor or somebody. So you had a 
commission that was hostile. We had a city manager

32:38.295 --> 32:42.123
that says, it's time for us to do planning. We 
haven't done it for 25 years. We're paying for it.

32:44.788 --> 32:53.025
Arlington has an extraordinary amount of bonded 
indebtedness, far more than any other city. 60% of

32:53.714 --> 32:58.262
the budget is used to retire bond and debt, you 
know, and the rule of thumb is 25%. But it happened

32:59.023 --> 33:01.207
because they bought that growth. Here this growth 
was coming anyway, but they subsidized the

33:01.227 --> 33:04.352
development community. They did a fiscal impact 
study in the late 70s that showed that the

33:04.793 --> 33:16.313
population of the city had grown, the population 
had grown 50% during this study period. Bonded

33:16.698 --> 33:21.948
indebtedness had gone up something like 900%, and 
per capita debt had gone up 400%. So nobody could

33:22.149 --> 33:28.802
say that the debt was occurring because of the 
growth. The debt was occurring because they

33:29.283 --> 33:31.968
subsidized too much of it. They just underwrote 
the growth at public expense. When this study was

33:35.969 --> 33:42.956
done, by the way, they boxed it up and shoved it in 
the closet. It was never released to the public.

33:44.378 --> 33:48.782
The public didn't know the significance of those 
fiscal implications. But Vandegrift did, and his

33:48.802 --> 33:57.831
last act as he left when that study was there, they 
changed some of the participation policies, and

33:48.802 --> 33:57.831
the city was paying less from 77 or 78 on. They paid 
less when Vandegrift left. From that point on, The

34:01.805 --> 34:06.094
developers had to pay a higher proportion of their 
costs. The manager knew changes had to occur. The

34:09.220 --> 34:16.394
council, which was politically responsive to the 
community, understood there was a growing

34:09.220 --> 34:16.394
groundswell of interest in preserving the 
quality of life. The people were afraid they were

34:16.414 --> 34:20.202
losing what had brought them to Arlington to start 
with. So, they went out, they recruited very

34:20.975 --> 34:29.866
heavily to bring in a really innovative, 
aggressive, you know, doer-oriented,

34:20.975 --> 34:29.866
results-oriented planer. And I competed with 
some real good people, including somebody that's

34:30.206 --> 34:35.412
up here in the Metroplex, Matt Plano. I'm not sure 
if you remember his name now. It's not my name

34:37.755 --> 34:39.057
today. He's the planer director in Plano. Planer 
director in Plano. But he's the North Central

34:41.620 --> 34:45.184
Texas chapter president. Yeah, I know. I'll 
remember. We'll fill that in. So the manager

34:49.105 --> 34:54.737
wanted somebody good and the council wanted 
somebody good, but they forgot to tell the

34:49.105 --> 34:54.737
commission that they wanted somebody good. In my 
first week in office or in town, they took me out to

34:55.097 --> 35:00.990
dinner, the planning commission did. They asked 
me what my plans were, what my philosophy was, what

35:01.010 --> 35:06.962
I liked and didn't like, various things. And like 
an idiot, I just told them, you know, hey, here's

35:07.415 --> 35:14.484
what I like, here's what I can do, here's where we 
can do better, here's where we're doing great. But

35:15.285 --> 35:35.970
after that dinner, the following week prior to the 
planning commission, I got visited by the

35:15.285 --> 35:35.970
chairman of the commission, the vice chairman, 
and they told me they were real disappointed in the

35:15.285 --> 35:35.970
answers I had given, that they wanted to make sure I 
understood how it was going to be in Arlington, and

35:15.285 --> 35:35.970
that, number one, nothing was broke, so therefore 
absolutely nothing was going to get fixed. And

35:36.625 --> 35:37.927
that I should understand that. And that if I wanted 
to be successful there, what I needed to do was to

35:38.668 --> 35:43.816
get involved in a hobby. Get involved with 
Arlington Initiative, which was a

35:45.219 --> 35:53.432
goals-oriented local citizen group that the last 
planning director, Jill Potthoff, had started.

35:53.472 --> 35:54.814
Get involved with APA. Anyway, do whatever I 
wanted to do outside local government. But not to

35:58.900 --> 36:06.650
get involved with anything that was going on that 
had been going on, that everybody was satisfied

35:58.900 --> 36:06.650
with the status quo. And that I would have real 
serious personal and professional problems if I

36:07.311 --> 36:14.440
messed with them. Well, I passed this on to the city 
manager, and the city manager said these people

36:14.460 --> 36:21.469
are dinosaurs, they're out of date, this change is 
coming. The council wants a change, and that's why

36:22.230 --> 36:27.557
he hired me, and he expected me to see me make those 
changes. So, yeah I started off in an adversarial

36:28.448 --> 36:34.917
relationship with the commission. And for the 
next two or three months it deteriorated because

36:34.937 --> 36:43.369
as I continued to bring new programs and ideas, 
they continued to tell me to drop dead and go to

36:34.937 --> 36:43.369
hell, you know, get lost. Then a real bad thing 
happened. The city manager who'd been there 20

36:46.473 --> 36:53.863
years resigned and went into the private sector, 
into the investment business. That was a career

36:53.883 --> 36:56.447
move he'd wanted to make for some time. So he made 
that transition. One of the assistant city

37:00.567 --> 37:07.175
managers became the acting manager for a period of 
about three or four months, five months, six

37:00.567 --> 37:07.175
months. During that period of time, I became so 
disgusted with my ineffectiveness with the

37:08.997 --> 37:16.647
commission and their ability to stop everything 
that I that I attempted to resign. I went upstairs

37:18.477 --> 37:20.839
and the manager said I'm through. Life is too 
short. I've got too much I want to accomplish. I'm

37:25.223 --> 37:30.288
going to blow off six months of my life here in an 
ineffective environment. And I said, the truth of

37:30.388 --> 37:32.970
it is I know I can't be effective here. These people 
are too skilled at maintaining the status quo.

37:36.934 --> 37:38.555
They're going to study us to death. Anything that 
we bring forward to them, they just give to a

37:38.575 --> 37:41.277
committee. And you won't see it for a couple of 
years. So the manager said that wasn't that he

37:46.934 --> 37:49.738
didn't share that view of my effectiveness, 
ineffectiveness. And he encouraged me to stay and

37:49.778 --> 37:53.544
lead everything they could do, et cetera. And he 
taught me to stay. Then five months later, we got a

37:55.546 --> 37:57.870
new city manager. I worked for him for about two 
months. I had a real blowout with the commission

37:59.292 --> 38:03.758
and council over whether or not we were going to do 
comprehensive planning. I went to the manager. I

38:04.820 --> 38:05.881
resigned again. And the new manager convinced me 
to stay. He said, you've only been here a month. You

38:10.468 --> 38:11.269
need more time. You need to be effective. We can do 
this. And here's what we can do to become more

38:13.552 --> 38:15.996
effective. And he got the council to go along with 
some things and put a lot of pressure on the

38:16.330 --> 38:19.775
commission. And so for the last year, we made 
progress. Slow, painful, drudging progress.

38:27.626 --> 38:31.331
Given me, if I had stayed there another couple of 
years, I could have been relatively effective. We

38:31.351 --> 38:36.939
could have had something in place in Arlington 
that I could have claimed credit for. But when this

38:38.321 --> 38:42.747
opportunity opened for work, it could be 
effective right away. It was a career

38:42.767 --> 38:44.349
advancement. It was a challenge. In truth, I was 
real pleased to get the chance to leave that

38:46.402 --> 38:49.967
environment. Now, Beaumont has got a good 
program. Arlington has got a good program in

38:52.290 --> 38:54.312
place. Rose Jacobson is now standing planning 
director. Ray Quay is the assistant over there.

38:59.699 --> 39:03.504
Ray is going to have a state-of-the-art 
comprehensive plan. For Arlington. For

39:05.086 --> 39:05.527
Arlington. It's going to take a year longer than I 
would have thought it would have taken, but the

39:05.707 --> 39:13.818
commission over there is still roadblocking it. 
There's been several resignations now. And the

39:16.253 --> 39:18.456
chairman is still hanging on. He wants to be there 
until the plan is finished. He was the biggest

39:20.779 --> 39:27.648
obstacle to completing the plan, and now he's 
stating his reputation on finishing the plan. He

39:27.688 --> 39:33.575
tried to stop it for years, and now it's the old 
thing we talk about in one of these other cities. If

39:33.595 --> 39:35.398
you're going to have something, you're in 
Beaumont. If you're going to have something, we

39:35.418 --> 39:38.121
may have something we can live with. So he's trying 
to make it something that he can live with. But it

39:41.966 --> 39:44.049
was very disappointing two years on my part. Real, 
real painful. And the planning director in

39:46.223 --> 39:49.112
Arlington is now Rose? Rose Jacobson. 
Outstanding. She is a hard worker, applies

39:51.802 --> 39:58.593
herself every day, and she knows more about 
playing each day than she did the day before.

39:58.693 --> 40:02.419
Constantly learning, constantly applying, and 
very strong. I laugh and call her the Dragon Lady

40:03.180 --> 40:10.591
sometimes, but she is a very effective 
administrator. Really a quality person. Very

40:11.653 --> 40:12.033
good. That's hopeful. Now to Fort Worth. Now to 
