40:14.918 --> 40:16.520
Worth, Bob? What are you doing here at Fort Worth? 
How is your... What is the perception of the

40:20.075 --> 40:23.081
planning program in Fort Worth? The history of 
Fort Worth have already documented the ancient

40:23.141 --> 40:33.561
history of planning in Fort Worth, so we needn't go 
back to the Gruen Plan or any of that. But what we

40:33.929 --> 40:44.460
need to do is sort of pick up on what happened during 
the regime of the

40:33.929 --> 40:44.460
previous planning director. Okay. The previous 
planning director was James Toll, and James

40:45.701 --> 40:51.828
inherited a losing program. They had fired 
Stephen Andradeus and Darryl Noe. Planning was at

40:55.752 --> 41:03.700
the low ebb, heartbreaking when you consider the 
history that you just mentioned, the growing

40:55.752 --> 41:03.700
plant, etc., Fort Worth had a history of effective 
planning, respected planning across the

41:04.456 --> 41:10.535
country. And in the latter, in the late 60s and then 
in the 70s, in particular the latter part of the

41:17.888 --> 41:19.750
70s. Every year planning got hurt a little bit more 
than the year before. We lost a little bit of the

41:23.775 --> 41:25.938
prestige that was over here. Andre just killed it, 
finished it off, wiped it out. And it's not so much a

41:31.604 --> 41:34.868
reflection on him as it was at the times. Times 
change. People change. Values change. And your

41:37.792 --> 41:39.854
planning program has to change with that. You have 
to know when to go with the flow, when to be able to do

41:41.530 --> 41:50.007
something, when to look for the programs that 
people do want instead of trying to push what's no

41:41.530 --> 41:50.007
longer acceptable. In Fort Worth, it's been very 
effective in the citizen participation. There's

41:54.576 --> 42:00.067
still a world class examples on how to involve 
citizens in planning. But during the Andrade's

42:00.788 --> 42:03.133
regime, credibility and support for the plane 
just evaporated, disappeared, it was destroyed.

42:07.519 --> 42:10.924
James Toll came in and... Where did he come from? He 
was in the Parks Department. Been here many years,

42:13.027 --> 42:26.185
hard-working young fella that really, with an 
urban design background, and he came in and took on

42:13.027 --> 42:26.185
this job and in four years or thereabouts created 
tremendous public support and respect for

42:26.992 --> 42:31.298
planning. Again, that's a good word, again. And I, 
looking at him when I was in Beaumont and over in

42:33.962 --> 42:39.610
Arlington, I admired the heck out of him. I thought 
objectively that he was the most effective

42:39.810 --> 42:51.447
planner that we had during the early 1980s, that he 
did more, accomplished more in a hard, hot,

42:51.697 --> 42:58.644
political context, he was able to do something and 
establish credibility for this program that had

42:51.697 --> 42:58.644
been lost.

43:01.547 --> 43:13.379
He did it by taking on the big projects, by having 
influence, by earning the respect of the

43:01.547 --> 43:13.379
development community, the respect of the 
business community, the respect of the elected

43:01.547 --> 43:13.379
officials, respect for his judgment. He dealt 
with a big picture, the Southwest freeways, the

43:13.659 --> 43:18.904
cultural districts, the growth management 
programs. He saw the concept of these people. He

43:20.806 --> 43:29.935
made him, he sold the sizzle, you know, he put the 
sizzle back into planning and got people excited

43:20.806 --> 43:29.935
about planning again. And this is the legacy I 
inherit. Now that I'm in here, I more than anything

43:33.358 --> 43:38.323
else have to implement the vision that he's left in 
place. And our major workload here is involving

43:39.264 --> 43:50.695
the area of the Southwest Freeway, trying to do 
something with our cultural district,

43:39.264 --> 43:50.695
continuing the progress that's been made in our 
downtown, and lastly and most importantly, is

43:51.113 --> 43:55.359
implementing a growth management system. An 
extraordinary idea. You know, there are two

43:57.041 --> 44:06.273
cities in this state that are working on growth 
management systems, Austin and Fort Worth, and

43:57.041 --> 44:06.273
you couldn't think of two cities in greater 
contrast than Austin and Fort Worth. And the Fort

44:07.414 --> 44:11.720
Worth program is going to be successful, and I 
don't know if the Austin will well be. And you would

44:11.740 --> 44:15.805
think that it ought to be reversed, that when it 
really comes down to it, And the citizens and the

44:16.274 --> 44:22.381
business community really see what's in this for 
Fort Worth that they might back off growth

44:16.274 --> 44:22.381
management, but they won't. I think if anybody 
backs off it, it'll be Fort Worth. I mean, it'll be

44:25.465 --> 44:26.386
Austin. The only thing, Austin will panic when 
they have an economic downturn. And they'll fill

44:30.070 --> 44:35.237
the baby out with a wash, and they'll do away with 
their interest and enthusiasm for growth

44:30.070 --> 44:35.237
management. While Fort Worth is going to build on 
its heritage and become the model for the

44:35.257 --> 44:41.404
southwest of growth management. Well, it has a 
legacy of many, many years of planning, and I think

44:42.447 --> 44:49.760
that it probably will hold them in good stead as 
they move forward. You have to build. See, Bob, the

44:51.623 --> 44:55.730
beauty of Fort Worth is you can build on these 
victories that have been out there in the past. We

44:56.772 --> 44:58.254
need to update our sector plans. We don't need to 
wait eight or nine years like they've done in the

44:58.314 --> 45:02.382
past to update those things. We need to go into an 
annual updating mode. We need to take our old

45:04.823 --> 45:17.418
comprehensive plan that was done in 55 and combine 
it with the sector plans and the district plans in

45:04.823 --> 45:17.418
the growth management system and come up with a 
modern, state-of-the-art, updatable

45:04.823 --> 45:17.418
comprehensive plan. We're going to do that as part 
of the growth management system here. You take

45:21.082 --> 45:30.913
these victories, you take the sector plans that 
everybody knows they've got awards for, and you

45:21.082 --> 45:30.913
build on those and say, we've got to update these 
things, and we've got to integrate these into the

45:21.082 --> 45:30.913
growth management system now. You take the 
Chamber's work on strategic... strategic plan

45:34.355 --> 45:41.383
for economic development that everybody likes 
and is proud of and you integrate that into the

45:34.355 --> 45:41.383
growth management system. You take the 
neighborhood planning programs that have

45:41.403 --> 45:49.992
struggled here a little bit in the inner city under 
the block grant program and you repackage those

45:41.403 --> 45:49.992
under the guise of growth management. That in fact 
inner city development and prioritizing and

45:50.132 --> 45:59.482
encouraging development to turn into itself is a 
key critical part of growth management. Unlike in

45:59.502 --> 46:03.366
Austin or someplace that's looking at the 
periphery of growth management, We're looking at

46:03.667 --> 46:06.252
growth performance management. We want to 
identify these target areas where we want growth

46:06.272 --> 46:10.639
to occur, including our inner city. We want to put 
programs in place that encourage and induce

46:10.940 --> 46:15.688
development to take place. You build on the 
successes, you find the things that are working,

46:15.708 --> 46:22.620
and you paint whatever that is you're working on 
with that brush. It's like in Beaumont, one of the

46:22.718 --> 46:31.187
things we did besides putting all those plans in 
place, we shifted the philosophy to economic

46:22.718 --> 46:31.187
development. I tried to change the name of the 
program, of the department, to the Department of

46:31.387 --> 46:36.873
Planning and Economic Development. We pushed 
UDACs, we pushed grants, partner with space

46:37.574 --> 46:41.197
grants. In a city in two years, in a city that had 
been hostile to grants, federal grants, we

46:48.588 --> 46:51.631
brought in something like $11 or $12 million in 
grants. And a department budget that had $600,000

46:52.071 --> 47:01.961
or $700,000 in budgets for those two years, we 
brought in $11 million in federal grants and money

46:52.071 --> 47:01.961
to that area. Not block grants, not categorical 
grants that we were entitled to. These were

47:07.967 --> 47:10.469
categorical grants. These were competitive 
grants where we competed with other cities. We

47:14.793 --> 47:16.755
took our park and open space plan And our action 
plan that we had, and we competed in the urban parks

47:17.208 --> 47:21.962
and recreation recovery program. And in the first 
funding period, the first six months or three

47:22.423 --> 47:32.331
months of funding cycle, there was something like 
$280,000 available for the Southwest, the entire

47:22.423 --> 47:32.331
Southwest.

